      "role": "user",
      "content": "it does look like it could be a timeout. i checked the ALB and the idle timeout is set to 60s, but our app expects connections to stay open longer than that for certain long-running tasks. \n\nalso, i've been looking at the VPC flow logs and noticed some weird, tiny spikes in packet loss that don't seem to follow a pattern. it's almost like something is poking at the connection randomly. any way to distinguish between a legitimate timeout and something else just causing jitter or packet drops?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The ALB idle timeout being 60s while your tasks run longer perfectly points to the load balancer terminating the connection. To distinguish this from random probing, look closely at the time correlation between the ALB timeout and the connection resets in your application logs. If the resets consistently happen shortly *after* the 60-second mark, it's the ALB. The small, random packet loss spikes in flow logs could indicate underlying network instability or something like a connection drain by an intermediate device, but the timeout is the most probable culprit.",
      "source": "target",
